This is a pretty angry, loaded post, Jack.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; WI the Vietnam War was as much a crusade as WWI and WWII?
">

How would you achieve this, Jack? The World Wars posed a clear threat
to the established order of powers. In the first case, belated
American entry had slightly more to do with submarines that the
Kaiser's designs for global dominion. The latter case, of course, was
an existential threat to the republic, like the Civil War.

Vietnam was a proxy war, like Iraq and Afghanistan; it didn't imperil
the republic directly nor threaten its survival. And if we want to win
on technical points, Vietnam wasn't a "war" to become a crusade in--it
was a vast overreach of executive branch power, a gradual escalation
of a half-hearted police-action into a clusterfuck, without a defined
enemy--"Communism" and "Dominoes" are not enemies, and the post-facto
creation of the Gulf of Tonkin Resolution to give ass-covering quality
to the already extant war, well...--or defined mission objective.

There's no crusade to effectively *win* in this case, and so it's hard
to mount one. A "Global Crusade Against Communism" would be just as
effective as other Wars on Abstract Nouns.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;  Where it was considered a duty to serve your country rather than a sign of
&gt; stupidity?
">

Jack, it is a duty to serve the republic. It is not a duty, however,
to serve the republic in a a travesty of a war, a mistake, and a lie.
It is only the duty to serve a dictatorship in those cases.

Free citizens do what they want; even within that frame, the Vietnam
War did include the draft, despite MacNamara's 200,000 Social Program.
Mind, the draft was less equitable than it had been during WWII, but
better than it was during the Civil War.

But America has a tradition of a relatively small standing military,
in proportion to population, compared to other uberpowers of the past.
The Founders and the first century or so of the Republic bequeathed,
in fact, a horror at a large standing army which remains central to
American political life 200+ years later. The late-coming of American
superpower status in a free, semi-universally voting republic
preempted the development of martial culture.

The Post-Vietnam Army wasn't really a Career Opportunity again until
the mid-1980s, once it got cleaned up--even then, low pay and
excruciatingly slow career advancement in peacetime do not make
regular enlistment economically appealing or sensible for most
Americans who go to the Ivies or the Little Ivies. [Additionally, the
increasingly jarring rightward shift of the American military makes it
a culturally unappealing organization for a lot of people on those
campuses.]

The all-volunteer era marks a time when many of the JCS and greater
numbers of the officers are not drawn from the service academies, but
from ROTC branches. The bitter legacy of Vietnam which led to the
removal of many ROTC and recruiters from upper tier university
campuses, has not been reversed, for a variety of reasons. In some,
though not all cases, this is a consequence of DADT, which has
increasingly been viewed as a discriminatory employment practice. This
reduces the interest of homosexuals in joining the armed forces, with
a ripple suppression on people who don't feel compelled to fight for a
republic that treats its citizens less than equitably. [Fair
disclosure: I'd have either applied to West Point or joined ROTC if I
didn't have a boyfriend; however, what would I be fighting for other
than homophobia and the destruction of my own rights as a
citizen?....I mean, hooray gay-bashing!] Likewise, the proliferation
of rape of women soldiers helps suppress female enrollment.

Let's condense: the army pays poorly, could get you killed, has
excellent (until 2001, hooray urine man!) health care, but is
wrenching on families. In a world in which both women and men serve,
but also women and men vote and women have  careers and professional
lives separate from their husbands, it makes the army a hard sell when
it is a homophobic, reactionary, misogynistic organization that either
would require both spouses to serve in the same branch in the hope of
similar post assignments, or to have a spouse (the wife) sacrifice
career ambitions to follow her husband post-to-post for a long time at
a relatively low income.

I'd have to look at the marriage numbers, but let's work with the
assumption that there's equity between the education and original
class of the husband and wife coming out of, say, Yale. It's highly
unlikely that you'll get a couple where either the wife or the husband
is willing to subsume their life and their education to be a wife on
base, for a cross-section of factors. It's just unappealing.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Is there any POD that would make such dedication normal rather than a
&gt; sign of stupidity?
">

A more militarized republic, probably, which would have so many other
impacts that this would be relatively pedestrian.

You would need either no Vietnam War or a wildly different outcome to
continue the draft, to forcibly make the US Army more equitable.

I also suspect that your strawman of "stupidity" is both a nasty
talking point and a little bit more than silly.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Is there a way to get an Army that represents all of the classes in America or
&gt; are we letting the &quot;volunteer&quot; nature serve as an excuse for our children avoiding &gt; service?
">

Well, to answer the first of essentially two questions, yeah, return
to the draft. No one wants that.

To answer the second question: that's crap! "We" aren't doing anything
in particular, just a whole mess of people making choices
independently of each other. There's sense to be made of this part,
Jack, other than as a sort of political temper tantrum.

"...excuse for our children avoiding the service" should set off a
string of alarm bells in anyone. The service hasn't been obligatory
for a while, so no one is "avoiding" anything; they're just making an
economic choice regarding their employer. Looking at 1972-August 2001,
Would you want a low-paying job with little chance of career
advancement over /years/ when you had obviously better opportunities
to start with, in an organization that is reactionary, macho,
homophobic, and misogynistic, if you could go work for Morgan Stanley,
Fleet Bank, JP Morgan, Random House, or go to graduate school instead?

There was a brief upsurge in commitment to military service following
Sept. 11. But the long twilight war with no bid contracts is not an
existential threat to the republic, and certainly not one that has
been managed competently; accordingly, it's underwhelming to people
who have other more viable options.

The all-volunteer army is not the most appealing employer in a
marketplace of employers who have incentives to treat and pay
employees better, in a society after third wave feminism. It doesn't
mean there aren't smart, honorably, dutiful people serving in the
army; it just means that it's a less appealing alternative with a BA
from Harvard, Williams, Stanford, or Northwestern.

You may see a slight shift following the abolition of DADT; that would
allow recruiters back to law schools, but it won't reopen a bunch of
ROTC chapters. You'd need the two to start seeing /an/ increase of any
sort from Harvard, Amherst, or Northwestern. Regardless, that increase
won't be /huge./

At least until Tehran and Damascus...

Of course, none of this takes into account things like Blackwater,
Ravenwood, and Triple Canopy.

