Company, out of Fort Lewis, Wash., was two days away from leaving for
Iraq. Swift and her platoon had been home less than a year, having
completed one 12-month tour of duty in February 2005, and now the
rumor was that they were headed to Baghdad to run a detention center.
The footlockers were packed. The company's 130 soldiers had been
granted a weekend leave in order to go where they needed to go, to say
whatever goodbyes needed saying. When they reassembled at 7 a.m. that
Monday, uniformed and standing in immaculate rows, Specialist Swift,
